transcript_sub: I think trust can be easy when someone consistently demonstrates honesty and reliability. On the other hand, past betrayals or inconsistent behavior can make it difficult to trust someone. What are your thoughts on this topic?
transcript_llm: Trust is a tricky thing, you know. I agree with you that consistency plays a huge role. Like, when someone is always truthful and dependable, it definitely makes it easier to trust them. But, on the flip side, if someone has let you down in the past or their actions don't match their words, it can really shake that foundation of trust. It's like building a house of cards, one shaky move can bring it all down. It also makes me think about how trust is not just about what someone does, but also about how they make you feel, you know? Like, even if everything seems fine on the surface, sometimes you just get this gut feeling that something's off. Trust is delicate, like a glass sculpture that can shatter with just one wrong move.

transcript_llm: Oh, thanks for the kind words! Growing herbs has been such a rewarding experience for me, both in the garden and in the kitchen. One tip I've found helpful is to make sure herbs get enough sunlight, usually around 6-8 hours a day, for optimal growth. I've also learned that regular pruning and harvesting of herbs actually encourage new growth, so don't be afraid to trim them back for a bushier plant. And finally, adding some organic compost or fertilizer every now and then can really boost their growth and flavor. It's all about experimenting and finding what works best for your specific herb garden, you know?
